Hello,

I'm writing a modular fully JavaScript-based operating system (Its more of a website than a real OS). 
When I started writing this project (On my mobile phone), there was no ES6 (Or I didn't know of it). 

The first example uses Eval. How can I avoid that? [This is my development suite for my OS](https://dotcdn.us/webos-prod/). In the [file](https://dotcdn.us/webos-prod/js/engine.js]) I have a eval, because I load the desired application with a request. The [file](https://dotcdn.us/webos-prod/apps/com.test.weather.hs) isn't a pure json, because it contains functions, which you cant do in json. So I cant use a JSON.parse. How can i avoid using eval in this case?

My second problem is security. I made a port of my webOS and created a "module" based clone, with only a command line [here](https://dotcdn.us/webos-core/). In all my modules, eg the [kernel module](https://dotcdn.us/webos-core/js/kernel.js), I use a special notation for classes/modules:

```js
const testModule = (function () {
  var modulePrivate = {
    // Things that have to be available to all classes of this module but not to anything else
  }
  var modulePublic = {
    TestClass: function () { // A class without any restrictions/access management
      var private = {
        // Things needed by this instance
      };

      var public = {
        // Publicly available functions/properties
      };
      return public;
    },
    AccessManagedClass: function (keys) { // A class without any restrictions/access management
      var private = {
        // Things needed by this instance
      };

      var public = {
        killProcess: function (name) {
           if (access.validate("taskManagement", keys) {
             // Validated keys
           }
        };
        // Publicly available functions/properties
      }
      return public;
    }
  }

  access.register("taskManagement");

  return modulePublic;
})();
```
```js
var test = testModule.TestClass();
var key = access.taskManagement();
var authorizedManager = testModule.AccessManagedClass(key);
authorizedManager.killProcess("think"); // whatever
```

How can I isolate this with classes. Security is very important in my case. Private things should stay private. 

Hoping for a better alternative & thank you a lot for reading all this shit ;D
